# 1️⃣ Concept Teaching (Simple + GATE-Oriented)

---

# 🔹 What is a Heap?

A Heap is a **Complete Binary Tree** that satisfies the **Heap Property**.

📌 Heap is not the same as BST.

---

# 🔹 Types of Heaps

---

## 1️⃣ Max Heap

Every parent node is greater than or equal to its children.

Example:

```text
        100
       /   \
      50    80
     / \   / \
    20 30 40 60
```

Property:

[
Parent \ge Children
]

Largest element always at root.

---

## 2️⃣ Min Heap

Every parent node is smaller than or equal to its children.

Example:

```text
        10
       /  \
      20   30
     / \   / \
    40 50 60 70
```

Property:

[
Parent \le Children
]

Smallest element at root.

---

# 🔹 Why Complete Binary Tree?

Heap must always be:

✅ Complete Binary Tree

❌ Not necessarily Balanced BST

---

# 🔹 Array Representation of Heap

Heap is generally stored in an array.

Example:

```text
        50
       /  \
      30   40
     / \
    10 20
```

Stored as:

```text
[50,30,40,10,20]
```

---

## Important Formulas

For node at index i:

### Parent

[
Parent = \left\lfloor \frac{i-1}{2} \right\rfloor
]

---

### Left Child

[
2i+1
]

---

### Right Child

[
2i+2
]

📌 Very frequently asked in GATE.

---

# 🔹 Heap Operations

---

## 1️⃣ Insertion

Steps:

1. Insert at last position
2. Heapify Up

Example:

```text
Insert 90
```

Move upward until heap property restored.

---

### Complexity

[
O(\log n)
]

---

## 2️⃣ Deletion

Usually delete root.

Steps:

1. Replace root with last node
2. Heapify Down

---

### Complexity

[
O(\log n)
]

---

# 🔹 Heapify

Process of restoring heap property.

Two types:

### Heapify Up

Used after insertion.

---

### Heapify Down

Used after deletion.

---

# 🔹 Priority Queue

A data structure where elements are removed based on priority.

Highest priority element served first.

---

## Heap as Priority Queue

Max Heap:

```text
Highest value → Highest priority
```

Min Heap:

```text
Lowest value → Highest priority
```

---

### Operations

| Operation | Complexity |
| --------- | ---------- |
| Insert    | O(log n)   |
| Delete    | O(log n)   |
| Peek      | O(1)       |

---

📌 Priority Queue is usually implemented using Heap.

---

# 🔹 Heap Sort

A sorting algorithm based on Heap.

---

## Steps

### Step 1

Build Max Heap.

---

### Step 2

Swap root with last element.

---

### Step 3

Reduce heap size.

---

### Step 4

Heapify root.

Repeat until sorted.

---

# 🔹 Example

Array:

```text
[4,10,3,5,1]
```

Build Max Heap:

```text
10
/ \
5  3
/ \
4  1
```

Repeated extraction gives sorted array.

---

# 🔹 Complexity of Heap Sort

---

### Best Case

[
O(n \log n)
]

### Average Case

[
O(n \log n)
]

### Worst Case

[
O(n \log n)
]

📌 Same in all cases.

---

# 🔹 Space Complexity

[
O(1)
]

In-place sorting.

---

# 🔹 Heap vs BST

| Heap                 | BST                 |
| -------------------- | ------------------- |
| Complete Binary Tree | Ordered Binary Tree |
| Root is max/min      | Sorted property     |
| Fast priority access | Fast searching      |
| Search = O(n)        | Search = O(log n)   |

---

# 🔹 Common GATE Traps

### Trap 1

Heap is NOT a BST.

---

### Trap 2

Heap only guarantees parent-child ordering.

Not complete sorting.

---

### Trap 3

Searching in heap is:

[
O(n)
]

NOT

[
O(\log n)
]

---

### Trap 4

Heap Sort is NOT stable.

